Consider the expanded structure of hexane.
%\begin{center}\chemfig{C(-[:90]H)(-[:180]H)(-[:-90]H)-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]H)-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]H)-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]H)-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]H)-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]H)-H   }\end{center}
A cycloalkane results from removing the left and right hydrogen while connecting the molecule in the form of a cycle:
\vspace{-0.5cm}\begin{center}\chemfig{H-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]@A)-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-C(-[:90]H)(-[:-90]@B)-H   }\end{center}
\chemmove{\draw[shorten >=4pt]
(A).. controls +(-90:1cm) and +(-90:1cm).. (B);}
\vspace{0.5cm}\\
As the most stable structure for six lines is the hexagon, the resulting structure of cyclohexane would be:
\begin{center}\chemfig{H_2C*6(-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-H_2C-[,,2])}\hspace{1cm} or \hspace{1cm}\chemfig{*6(------)}  \hspace{0.5cm}\textcolor{blue}{cyclohexane}\end{center}
